<h2 id="overview">{{ state.name }} Lemon Law Overview</h2>

{% if state.hasLemonLaw %}
<p>{{ state.name }} has a lemon law designed to protect consumers who purchase new vehicles that turn out to have serious, unrepairable defects. {{ state.lemonLawSummary }}</p>

<p>The purpose of lemon laws is to hold manufacturers accountable when they sell vehicles with substantial defects that cannot be corrected after a reasonable number of repair attempts. If your vehicle qualifies as a "lemon," you may be entitled to a full refund, a replacement vehicle, or a cash settlement.</p>
{% else %}
<p>{{ state.name }} does not have a specific state lemon law. However, consumers may still have protection under the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act, which applies to all states and covers products sold with written warranties.</p>
{% endif %}

<h2 id="qualifies">What Qualifies as a Lemon in {{ state.name }}?</h2>

<p>Generally, a vehicle may qualify as a lemon in {{ state.name }} if it meets the following criteria:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Substantial defect:</strong> The vehicle has a defect or condition that substantially impairs its use, value, or safety. Minor cosmetic issues typically do not qualify.</li>
  <li><strong>Covered period:</strong> The defect was reported to the manufacturer or an authorized dealer during the warranty period. Each state defines this window differently.</li>
  <li><strong>Reasonable repair attempts:</strong> The manufacturer or dealer was given a reasonable number of opportunities to repair the defect. This typically means 3-4 attempts for the same problem, or the vehicle has been out of service for a cumulative total of 30 or more days.</li>
  <li><strong>Not caused by owner:</strong> The defect was not caused by abuse, neglect, unauthorized modification, or an accident caused by the owner.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="how-to-file">How to File a Lemon Law Claim in {{ state.name }}</h2>

<p>If you believe your vehicle qualifies as a lemon, follow these steps to protect your rights and build the strongest possible case:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Document every repair visit.</strong> Keep copies of all repair orders, invoices, and correspondence with the dealer and manufacturer. Note the date, mileage, description of the problem, and what was done.</li>
  <li><strong>Send written notice to the manufacturer.</strong> Most state lemon laws require you to send a formal written notice to the manufacturer (not just the dealer) describing the defect and requesting it be repaired. Send this via certified mail with return receipt.</li>
  <li><strong>Allow a final repair attempt.</strong> After sending written notice, you must typically allow the manufacturer one final opportunity to repair the defect.</li>
  <li><strong>File for arbitration or legal action.</strong> If the final repair attempt fails, you can file for manufacturer-sponsored arbitration, state-sponsored arbitration, or pursue legal action. Many states require you to attempt arbitration before filing a lawsuit.</li>
  <li><strong>Consider hiring a lemon law attorney.</strong> Most lemon law attorneys work on contingency, meaning they only get paid if you win. Under most state lemon laws, the manufacturer is required to pay your attorney fees if you prevail.</li>
</ol>

