<h2 id="remedies">Remedies Available Under {{ state.name }} Lemon Law</h2>

<p>If your claim is successful, you may be entitled to one of the following remedies:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Full refund:</strong> The manufacturer refunds the full purchase price of the vehicle, including taxes, registration fees, and finance charges. A reasonable offset for the miles you drove before the first repair attempt may be deducted.</li>
  <li><strong>Replacement vehicle:</strong> The manufacturer provides a comparable replacement vehicle of equal value and similar features.</li>
  <li><strong>Cash settlement:</strong> In some cases, manufacturers offer a cash settlement to resolve the claim without providing a full refund or replacement. Always have an attorney review settlement offers before accepting.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="federal">Federal Lemon Law Protection</h2>

<p>In addition to {{ state.name }}'s state lemon law, you may also have rights under the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act. This federal law applies when:</p>

<ul>
  <li>A product is sold with a written warranty</li>
  <li>The product fails to conform to the warranty after a reasonable number of repair attempts</li>
  <li>The warranty provider (manufacturer) refuses to honor the warranty terms</li>
</ul>

<p>The Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act can apply to both new and used vehicles that are still under manufacturer warranty. It also allows consumers to recover attorney fees and court costs if they prevail.</p>

<h2 id="tips">Tips for Strengthening Your Lemon Law Claim</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Always report problems in writing.</strong> Email or written service requests create a paper trail that is harder to dispute than verbal complaints.</li>
  <li><strong>Take your vehicle to authorized dealers only.</strong> Repairs performed by independent shops may weaken your claim, as the manufacturer can argue they did not have a proper opportunity to fix the issue.</li>
  <li><strong>Do not accept verbal promises.</strong> If a dealer promises that a problem will be fixed or monitored, ask them to document it on the repair order.</li>
  <li><strong>Keep a detailed log.</strong> Record every instance of the defect, including dates, circumstances, and any safety concerns. Photos and video evidence can be valuable.</li>
  <li><strong>Act quickly.</strong> Lemon law protections have time limits. The sooner you begin the claims process, the stronger your position.</li>
</ol>

